<dl id="n36207g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36207g">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36207g"> 207(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Bauble <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n36207g"><li>FW 536.08 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/lexrB.htm#n36207g">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/l39rB.htm#n36207g">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n36207g">MS BL 47484b-432</ms> </li><li>JJA 59:172 <a name="rBd14" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rBd14">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rB/rBd14.htm#n36207g">Draft: III&sect;3B.14</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The Liberal Catholics.]</font> But back to <mark>the bubble</mark>. This edifice&mdash;a thin vaporous and variously coloured affair which first encompasses then transcends the church building&mdash;is compounded of matter belonging to the various Theosophical planes &mdash; mental, astral, and etheric. And at a later stage of the service, &ldquo;the matter of still higher levels is introduced&rdquo;. &hellip; The general plan &hellip; suggests a basilica. It is said that the well known Church of Santa Sofia at Constantinople &ldquo;was erected in imitation of one of there spiritual edifices&rdquo;. If one can imagine that church made of clear blue gelatin, that will afford a fair idea of the eucharistic edifice. <small> Charles W. Ferguson, <a name="CFCT" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CFCT"><cite title="source">The Confusion of Tongues</cite></a> (1928; rpt. May 1929) 285-7</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
